<Author>JYardley
<Content>A place in my heart I have stayed at the St Pierre on every visit to New Orleans for nearly fifteen years now, whether on business or for pleasure, and I would not stay anywhere else. Picture a Tennessee Williams stage set with friendly management: the rooms are converted from slave quarters, around pretty courtyards. The hotel is a short walk from the crazy heart of Bourbon Street, but it's location is actually in the picturesque, residential heart of the French Quarter, which sadly most tourists never see. It's quiet. It's also quaint. Some of the floors slope a little. This won't be to the taste of people who enjoy anonymous convention hotels where you can order in room service while the doors slam all night, or ritzy 5-star places with waiters in penguin suits. The St Pierre is about atmosphere, informality, kindness. What it lacks in amenities (there's a breakfast room but no restaurant), it makes up for in magic. If you want plush, go elsewhere. If you want somewhere clean and comfortable that truly belongs in the Vieux Carre, this is the hotel for you. 
